-- Nordstrom approaches potential buyers for its credit cards sale -Bloomberg
-- By Kanika Sikka and Rohit T.K. in Bangalore
-- Fri May 23, 2014 09:31PM EDT
-- None



May 23 (Reuters) - Upscale department store operator Nordstrom Inc <JWN.N> is reaching out to potential buyers for its store-branded credit cards, Bloomberg reported on Friday, citing sources familiar with the matter.

Nordstrom has approached Citigroup Inc <C.N>, JPMorgan Chase & Co <JPM.N>, Capital One Financial Corp <COF.N> and Toronto-Dominion Bank <TD.TO>, among other companies to test interest in its credit cards, the report said. (http://link.reuters.com/vew59v) The company, which has yet to set a date to solicit initial offers, is informally approaching buyers for the portfolio, Bloomberg said, citing one of the sources.  Nordstrom plans to reach out to other top issuers of credit cards and private-label cards, Bloomberg reported.  Nordstrom said on May 15 it was seeking a financial partner for its credit card receivables. [ID:nBw7glPMQa] The company had said it was working with Goldman Sachs & Co and Guggenheim Securities LLC as financial advisors for a potential deal for its credit card portfolio, which totals about $2 billion. Target Corp <TGT.N> had sold its consumer credit card portfolio to TD Bank Group for $5.7 billion in March 2013.